<hr />
<dl style="margin-left: 2 em">
  <a name="point"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POINT(S)</dt>
  <dd>1) In British maritime (particularly RN) usage, now largely obsolete, a term 
  sometimes applied to the fly corners of a flag or ensign  (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf5.html#fly">fly 1)</a>&rsquo;) <br />
  2) The term may also be employed (either in the singular or plural as appropriate) to describe the 
  fly of a triangular/swallow-tailed pennant, a swallow-tailed flag or one with three even tails 
  (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp2.html#pennant">pennant</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs9.html#swallowtail">swallow-tail(ed)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs9.html#swallowtail-tongue">swallowtail and tongue</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt5.html#tripletailed">triple-tongued 1)</a>�<p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3796.gif"><img src="../images/v/vxt-d3796.gif" alt="Points example" border="0" height="108" /></a> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3797.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3797.gif" alt="Points example" border="0" height="108" /></a><br>
  <a href="gb-ensh1.html#white"><em>White Ensign c1750</em></a><em>, UK (fotw); Flag of
  </em><a href="sk-bs-bb.html"><em>Bansk� Bel�</em></a><em>, Slovakia (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr/><a name="pointofhonor"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POINT OF HONOUR</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh4.html#honorpoint">honour point</a>&rsquo;.
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="pointed"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POINTED (or POINTS)</dt>
  <dd>1) In vexillology the terms used to indicate the number of points on a star or 
  star-like charge, for example a five-pointed star or a star of five points &ndash; but see 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-r.html#rays">rays 1)</a>&rsquo; (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs6.html#star">star 1)</a>&rsquo;) 
  <br />2) In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="#pointinpoint">point-in-point</a>&rsquo;.
  <br />3) A term sometimes (incorrectly) used to describe the point of an arrow � see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb2.html#barbed">barbed</a>&rsquo;.
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d3752.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3752.gif" alt="Pointed example" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3804.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3804.gif" alt="Pointed example" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br><em>National Flag of <a href="vn.html">Vietnam</a> (fotw);
  National Arms of <a href="es).html">Spain</a> (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="pointinpoint"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POINT-IN-POINT (or POINTED)</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic terms for when the division of a shield forms a chevron - usually embowed - 
  at its base - pointed or enty (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb3.html#base">base</a>&rsquo;, &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvch.html#chevron">chevron 1)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-e.html#embowed">embowed</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-i.html#impale">impale</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-q.html#quartering">quartering 1)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs3.html#shield">shield 1)</a>&rsquo;)
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-dv246.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-dv246.gif" alt="Pointed example" border="0" width="267" height="107" />
  </a><br />
  <em>Flag and Arms of <a href="de-nw.html">North Rhine�Westphalia</a>, Germany (fotw 
  &amp; CS)</em></p></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="pole"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POLE </dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf4.html#flagpole">flag pole</a>&rsquo;. </dd>

  <hr /><a name="polemast"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POLE MAST (or POLEMAST) </dt>
  <dd>A flagpole that is straight and clear of any projections such as cross bars, 
  yards, or gaffs (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvcq.html#crossbar">cross bar</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf4.html#flagpole">flag pole</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-g.html#gaff">gaff</a>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-y.html#yard">yard</a>&rsquo;).
  <p><em>Please note that this term was originally introduced 
  to describe a mast or masts on those steam vessels not equipped with an auxiliary 
  sailing rig.</em></p>
  <p><a href="../images/v/vxt-d2338.jpg">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2338.jpg" alt="Pole mast" border="0" width="182" height="108" /></a>
  <br><em>HMS Devastation 1871 � 1908 (Wikipedia)</em>  
  <em>&nbsp;</em></p>
  </dd>

  <hr /><a name="policeflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POLICE FLAG (ENSIGN or PENNANT) </dt>
  <dd>A flag or ensign, different from the national/state flag or government ensign (or 
  a variant thereof) or a pennant, which specifically identifies the installations or 
  vessels of a country&rsquo;s police service (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-n.html#nationalflag">national flag</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve2.html#gvtensign">government ensign</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve2.html#serensign">service ensign</a>&rsquo; under 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve2.html#ensign">ensign</a>&rsquo;, and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs7.html#stateflag">state flag</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d468b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d468b.gif" alt="Police flag" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2187.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2187.gif" alt="Police flag" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4315.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4315.gif" alt="Police flag" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br />
  <em>Police Flag, <a href="mt_polic.html">Malta</a> (fotw); 
  Flag of the <a href="ca_rcmp.html#equit">Police Mounted Branch</a>, Canada (fotw); 
  Police Vessel Pennant, <a href="th_polic.html#pvp">Thailand</a> (fotw)
  </em>   
  </dd>

  <hr /><a name="politicalflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POLITICAL FLAG </dt>
  <dd>The flag, either official (formally adopted) or unofficial (spontaneously 
  displayed by supporters), of a political party or movement&nbsp; 
  � but see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp8.html#protestflag">protest flag</a>&rsquo; and the notes below (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs0.html#sash">sash 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr1.html#realmbanner">realm banner black-red-gold</a>&rsquo;  and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvt5.html#tribalflag">tribal flag</a>&rsquo;). </dd>
  <dd>&nbsp;<p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d248.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d248.gif" alt="[political flags]" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="../images/v/vxt-d248d.gif"><img src="../images/v/vxt-d248d.gif" alt="[political flags]" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="../images/v/vxt-d4000.gif"><img src="../images/v/vxt-d4000.gif" alt="[political flags]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Flag of <a href="za}anc.html">African National Congress</a>, RSA (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="hr}ms.html">Me&#273;imurje Party</a>, Croatia (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="us}lnsg.html">Libertarian National Socialist Green Party</a>, USA (fotw).</em>
  <p><em><strong>Notes<br>a) </strong>In both historical and/or contemporary terms, 
  a political flag and a trade union flag can often be very closely linked &ndash; see 
  &lsquo;</em><a href="vxt-dvt2.html#tradeunionflag"><em>trade union flag</em></a><em>&rsquo;.<br>
  <strong>b)</strong> Protests often have a political motivation, and therefore, the difference between this and a protest flag is often blurred.</em></p>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="politicalsash"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POLITICAL SASH </dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs0.html#sash">sash 2)</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1375b.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1375b.gif" alt="Politica sash" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br /><em>Political Sash of the Women&rsquo;s Suffragette Movement 1917, US</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="pomme"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POMME(S)</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term for a green disc (or discs)  � a roundel (or roundels) vert 
  (see also �<a href="vxt-dvb5.html#bezant">bezant</a>�, �<a href="vxt-dvh6.html#hurt">hurt</a>�, �<a href="vxt-dvp4.html#plates">plates</a>� and 
  �<a href="vxt-dvr4.html#roundel">roundel 3)</a>�)
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3284.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3284.gif" alt="pomme" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3285.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3285.gif" alt="pomme" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br><em>Example; Flag of <a href="de-gb-04.html">Uelsen</a>, Germany (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="pommed"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POMMED</dt>
  <dd>A term sometimes used in place of the usual heraldic term pommeled to indicate the pommel of a sword or dagger &ndash; but see 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh2.html#hilted">hilted</a>&rsquo; 
  and following note (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-h.html#hafted">hafted</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs3.html#shafted">shafted</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2699a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2699a.gif" alt="pommed" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4001.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4001.gif" alt="pommed" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br><em>Arms of </em><a href="hr-si.html"><em>�ibenik-Knin</em></a><em>, Croatia (fotw);
  Flag of <a href="nl-nh-hl.html">Haarlem</a>, The Netherlands (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="pommeled"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POMMELED</dt>
  <dd>The heraldic term for the pommel of a sword or dagger � but see
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvh2.html#hilted">hilted</a>&rsquo; and its following note.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2083.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2083.gif" alt="Kalnik, Croatia" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2954.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2954.gif" alt="Ill-Birgu, Malta" border="0" height="108" />
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4843.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4843.gif" alt="Pommel" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br>
  <em>Flag of <a href="hr-kc-kn.html">Kalnik</a>, Croatia (fotw);
  Flag of <a href="mt-03.html">Il-Birgu</a>, Malta (fotw); 
  Flag of <a href="hr-pz-ka.html">Kaptol</a>, Croatia (fotw)
  </em>
  <p><em>Please note that a pommel is the usually (but not invariably) heavy, disk-like projection above the hilt which helps balance the blade, fixes that hilt&rsquo;s binding and act as a weapon in its own right.   </em></p>
  </dd>
  
  <hr />
  <a name="port"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">PORT</dt>
  <dd>A heraldic term, and derived from the French <em>porte</em> (or door), for the entrance to a castle, tower or other building (see also &lsquo;<span class="style2"><a href="vxt-dva1.html#ajoure">ajour&#233;</a></span>&rsquo; and &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvl2.html#litten">litten</a>&rsquo;). 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2906.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2906.gif" alt="[port example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4401a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4401a.gif" alt="[port example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4401.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4401.gif" alt="[port example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <br>
  <em>Flag of  <a href="pt-ajz.html">Aljezur</a>, Portugal (fotw); 
  Arms and Flag of <a href="hr-zg-zg.html">Zagreb</a>, Croatia (fotw)</em></dd>
  
  <hr />
  <a name="portcullis"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">PORTCULLIS  </dt>
  <dd>A sliding, openwork lattice intended to defend the gateway of a fortified structure � in heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#latticed">latticed</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4473.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4473.gif" alt="[portcullis]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4474.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4474.gif" alt="[portcullis]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br>
  <em>Flag of <a href="si-107.html">Rogatec</a>, Slovenia (fotw); Arms of  
  <a href="si-061.html#coa">Ljubljana</a>, Slovenia (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr />
  <a name="portcullised"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">PORTCULLISED</dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see �<a href="vxt-dv-l.html#latticed">latticed</a>� (also �<a href="vxt-dvp5.html#portcullis">portcullis</a>�). 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4475.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4475.gif" alt="[portcullised]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
