  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="positionofhonor"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POSITION OF HONOUR (OR HONOR) </dt>
  <dd>The position in which the most senior flag, emblem or coat of arms &ndash; usually 
  a national flag, emblem or coat of arms - is to be placed - sometimes called 
  the place of honour. The particulars vary 
  slightly in detail, legal status and extent from country to country; however, 
  the general principles remain the same and are listed in 
  <a href="vxt!dv-2.html">Appendix II</a> (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr6.html#rulesofetiquette">rules of etiquette<a/>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp6.html#precedence">precedence</a>&rsquo;).
  <p><em>Please note &ndash; not to be confused with the honour point &ndash; see 
  &lsquo;</em><a href="vxt-dvh4.html#honorpoint"><em>honour point</em></a><em>&rsquo;.</em></p>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="positional"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POSITIONAL FLAG (or COLORS)</dt>
  <dd>1) In US army usage, that flag which corresponds to a particular position 
  held, rather than to the rank of the officer who currently holds it &ndash; but see 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva3.html#appointmentflag">appointment flag</a>&rsquo; (also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-r.html#rankflag">rank flag 1)</a>&rsquo;). </dd>
  <dd>2) See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvd3.html#distinguishingflag">distinguishing flag 1)</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d249.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d249.gif" alt="[positional flag example]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2122.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2122.gif" alt="[positional flag example]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2123.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2123.gif" alt="[positional flag example]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br />
  <em><a href="us^arsg.html">Army Surgeon General</a>, US (fotw); 
  <a href="us^secar.html#under">Under Secretary of the Army</a>, US (fotw); 
  <a href="us^sma.html">Sergeant Major of the Army</a>, US (fotw)</em></p>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="postflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POST FLAG </dt>
  <dd>
  <p>
  1) In US military usage, that size of national flag flown regularly over army and marine corps posts &ndash; 
  8.95 feet (2.72m) wide by 17 feet (5.18m) long for the army and 10 feet (3 m) wide by 19 feet (5.8 m) long
  for the marine corps (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-g.html#garrisonflag">garrison  flag</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvsb.html#stormflag">storm flag</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-w.html#warflag">war flag</a>&rsquo;).
  <br>
  2) See &lsquo;<a href="#postalflag">postal flag</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d510.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d510.gif" alt="[current US flag]" border="0" height="108" /></a>&nbsp;<a href="../images/v/vxt-d875.gif"><img src="../images/v/vxt-d875.gif" alt="postal flag of France" border="0" height="108"/></a><br />
  <a href="us.html">National Flag</a> of the USA (fotw);  <em>
  <a href="fr~post.html">Post/Postal Flag</a> , France (fotw) </em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="postalflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POSTAL FLAG (ENSIGN or PENNANT)</dt>
  <dd>The distinguishing flag, ensign or pennant of a country&rsquo;s postal services &ndash; a mail flag/pennant or post 
  flag/pennant (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dva1.html#airmailflag">air mail flag</a> and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve2.html#serensign">service ensign</a>&rsquo; under &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve2.html#ensign">ensign</a>&rsquo;).
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4608.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4608.gif" alt="postal flag" border="0" height="108"/></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1805.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1805.gif" alt="postal flag" border="0" height="108"/></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d251.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d251.gif" alt="[postal flag - Denmark]" border="0" height="108"></a>
  <br />
  <em>Postal Flag, <a href="gb-rmail.html">UK</a> (fotw); 
  Postal Flag/Ensign 1920 � 1939, </em> <a href="de-dz~po.html"><em>Danzig</em></a><em> (fotw); 
  Postal Flag/Ensign, <a href="dk_post.html">Denmark</a> (fotw)</em>
  </dd>


  <hr /><a name="posthorn"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POST HORN</dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvb8.html#buglehorn">bugle horn</a>&rsquo;.
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3204a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3204a.gif" alt="[hunting horn example]" border="0" height="108" /></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d3204.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d3204.gif" alt="[hunting horn example]" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Arms and Flag of <a href="pl-sl-ty.html">Tychy</a>, Poland (fotw)</em></p></dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="postmedievalshield"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POST-MEDIEVAL SHIELD</dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvr2.html#renaissanceshield">Renaissance shield</a>&rsquo;.
  <p> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d4488.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d4488.gif" alt="postal office flag - Belgium" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em>Arms of <a href="hr-vu-il.html#coa">Ilok</a>, Croatia (fotw)</em>
  </dd>  
  
  <hr /><a name="postofficeflag"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POST OFFICE FLAG </dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="#postalflag">postal flag</a>&rsquo;.
  <p> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d2816.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d2816.gif" alt="postal office flag - Belgium" border="0" height="108" /></a><br />
  <em><a href="be_poff.html">Post Office/Postal Flag, Belgium</a> (fotw)</em>
  </dd>

  <hr /><a name="postalpennant"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POST PENNANT </dt>
  <dd>See &lsquo;<a href="#postalflag">postal flag</a>&rsquo;.
  <p> 
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1806.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1806.gif" alt="postal pennant - Italy" border="0" height="108" /></a><br /><em>Post/<a href="it~.html#post">Postal Pennant, Italy</a> (fotw)</em>
  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="postures"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POSTURES </dt>
  <dd>A 16th/17th Century term for the formal flag waving expected of a colour bearer 
  for reasons of either bravado or dignity (see also 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#color">colour 2)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc5.html#colors">colour bearer</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvc6.html#companycolors">company colours</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve2.html#ensign">ensign 4)</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf4.html#flagtossing">flag tossing</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvp1.html#pavisade">pavisade</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvs6.html#stand">stand 1)</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvsb.html#streamer">streamer 
  2)</a>&rsquo;). </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="potent"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POTENT</dt>
  <dd>1) The heraldic term for a fur that is shown as a series of crutch-shaped 
  charges and usually (but not exclusively) seen in blue on a white or silver 
  field (see also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dve4.html#ermine">ermine</a>&rsquo;, 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvf8.html#furs">furs</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dv-v.html#vair">vair</a>&rsquo;).<br />
    2) The term may also be used when the edge of an ordinary is shown with 
  crutch-shaped extensions � but see note below (also &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvct.html#crosspotent">cross potent</a>&rsquo; and 
  &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvo2.html#ordinary">ordinary</a>&rsquo;). 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d957.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d957.gif" border="0" alt="example" width="86" height="108"></a>&nbsp;
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1349a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1349a.gif" border="0" alt="example" height="108"></a>

  <span class="style3">
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1349.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1349.gif" border="0" alt="example" height="108"></a></span><br>
  <em>Example; Flag and Arms of <a href="pt-ppsuv.html">Unhais-o-Velho</a>, Portugal (fotw)
  <p>
  Please note with regard to 2) that this term is never used alone, but always with the 
  ordinary being blazoned, for example a fess-potent as illustrated above&rsquo;.</em>  </dd>
  
  <hr /><a name="potentcross"></a>
  <dt style="font-weight: bold">POTENT CROSS</dt>
  <dd>In heraldry see &lsquo;<a href="vxt-dvct.html#crosspotent">cross potent</a>&rsquo;. 
  <p>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1536a.gif">
  <img src="../images/v/vxt-d1536a.gif" border="0" alt="Wielka Nieszawka arms, poland" height="108"></a>
  <a href="../images/v/vxt-d1536b.gif">
